SIMPLE: scoff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scoff
<hw>Scoff</hw> <pr>(?; 115)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>scof</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>schof</ets>, OHG.
<ets>scoph</ets>, Icel. <ets>skaup</ets>, and perh. to E.
<ets>shove</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Derision; ridicule; mockery;
derisive or mocking expression of scorn, contempt, or
reproach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With <qex>scoffs</qex>, and scorns, and contumelious taunts.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An object of scorn, mockery, or derision.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>scoff</qex> of withered age and beardless youth.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scoff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scoff
<hw>Scoff</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scoffed</conjf> <pr>(?; 115)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scoffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Dan. <ets>skuffe</ets> to
deceive, delude, Icel. <ets>skopa</ets> to scoff, OD.
<ets>schoppen</ets>. See <er>Scoff</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To
show insolent ridicule or mockery; to manifest contempt by derisive acts
or language; -- often with <xex>at</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Truth from his lips prevailed with double sway,⟦br⟧
And fools who came to <qex>scoff</qex>, remained to pray.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God's better gift they <qex>scoff</qex> at and refuse.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To sneer; mock; gibe; jeer. See
<er>Sneer</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scoff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scoff
<hw>Scoff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To treat or address with derision;
to assail scornfully; to mock at.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>scoff</qex> religion is ridiculously proud and
immodest.</q> <rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scoffer</ent>⟦br⟧
